{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472464"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:58:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:58:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1471"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1471"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.04,0.14,0.1,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106918"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1471"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1471"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89404"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"769"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"6299"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"12946"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40943"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106918"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her routine antenatal care. She is 20 weeks pregnant with her second child. Her morphology scan reveals a healthy fetus with segmental leg length discrepancy. The parents are counselled about the likely cause of this abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt birth, the neonate is examined and found to have leg length discrepancy and foot ray deletion. The neonate appears otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits. Plain radiographs are performed and show the following (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Congenital tibial bowing","Proximal focal femoral deficiency","Congenital pseudarthrosis of the tibia","Congenital short femur","Hypoplastic fibula"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe radiograph shows a small \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoplastic fibula, \u003C/strong\u003Especifically noticeable on the AP image, classifying this as a Type I fibular hypoplasia. Hypoplastic fibula, also known as fibular hemimelia, is a congenital lower limb abnormality characterised by the partial or complete absence of the fibula. It is a rare occurrence, with an incidence reported at 5.7-20 per 1,000,000 live births, and has a male predominance. In this case, the antenatal scan showing segmental leg length discrepancy and the postnatal findings of leg length discrepancy and foot ray deletion are highly suggestive of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital tibial bowing\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where the tibia is curved, usually anterolaterally. While it can cause leg length discrepancy, it would not typically present with foot ray deletion. Moreover, the radiograph shows a hypoplastic fibula rather than a bowed tibia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProximal focal femoral deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E (PFFD) is a rare congenital anomaly characterised by failure of normal development of the proximal femur. While it can cause significant leg length discrepancy, it primarily affects the femur rather than the fibula. The radiograph in this case clearly shows a hypoplastic fibula, which is not a feature of PFFD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital pseudarthrosis of the tibia\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where there is a failure of normal bone formation in the tibia, leading to fracture and non-union. While it can cause leg length discrepancy, it primarily affects the tibia and would not typically present with foot ray deletion or fibular abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital short femur\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where the femur is shorter than normal from birth. While this would cause leg length discrepancy, it would not explain the foot ray deletion or the hypoplastic fibula seen on the radiograph.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe major concern in fibular hypoplasia is the instability of the ankle joint. Management depends on the severity of the condition and may range from orthotic devices to surgical interventions, including limb lengthening procedures or amputation in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fibular hypoplasia (or fibular hemimelia) is the partial or complete absence of the fibula.","Fibular hypoplasia is often detected antenatally and confirmed at birth with limb shortening and limb-length discrepancy.","Fibular hypoplasia can be classified as type I (minimal hypoplasia) or type II (complete absence of the fibula)."],"references":["Fuller CB, Shannon CE, Paley D. Lengthening reconstruction surgery for fibular hemimelia: a review. Children (Basel). 2021 Jun 2;8(6):467. doi: 10.3390/children8060467. Available at: https://www.mdpi.com/2227-9067/8/6/467","\u00d6zdemir M, Kavak RP, Din\u00e7 E. Postaxial hypoplasia of the lower extremity (fibular hemimelia) presenting in a young adult male. Radiol Case Rep. 2019 Aug;14(8):1027\u20131030. doi: 10.1016/j.radcr.2019.05.035. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1930043319301177"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89404"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1471"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18438"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18438"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/06826de1-78dc-419a-ae8f-ebaaf94a9700.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/06826de1-78dc-419a-ae8f-ebaaf94a9700.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":609,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89404"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T07:55:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T07:56:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1471"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106918"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading